^-{          How to Compete After Your RHO Doubles          
What Should You Do?

Introduction}
^-|fp||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|In some cases, after your RHO doubles, the auction will continue very differently than if the opponent had passed. At other times, you can make the same call that you would have done if the opponent hadn't taken any action.|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

Conventions such as 2/1 game forcing, 1NT forcing, Jacoby 2NT, and inverted minors all should be off after an opponent's takeout double. This is also true if the RHO had made an overcall. You definitely are entitled to count for distribution when you have a fit--counting for length and shortness.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

You certainly want to make life difficult for your left-hand opponent (LHO). Once his partner has doubled, he is going to bid (he has to bid if you pass). But, the opponents probably have a fit somewhere, so they're going to try to find it, and it's a very good thing to do if you can make life more difficult for them. In addition, you'll never go wrong following support with support; you'd like to let partner know that you have a fit and show him your support immediately if possible.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

Vulnerability is relevant, as always, but when you make voluntary bids in suits the opponents have indicated, you need to know what you are doing. You need to have a suit that you're willing to play in at that level even if opener has a singleton.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

Next is the summary of our different responses when partner makes an opening bid in a suit and the opponent makes a takeout double.|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: ^*NWe feel we learn and retain the information better if it is explained at a table. Therefore, you will see Bergen's recommendations illustrated at a table. Simply, a hand is constructed for you and you are asked to select to our response after our partner's opening bid is doubled by your RHO. Okay then get set and go.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


